name: 'Tomorrow is Built Today' exhibition of Black-led self-build
description: Open House of 13 Nubia Way  and oral history exhibition of Europe's largest black-led community self-build for rent  iintiative including archive material and new video. https://sites.gold.ac.uk/inlivingmemory/tomorrow-is-built-today/

name: 1 Halliwick Road
description: A low energy refurbishment of an Edwardian house, with rear extension and loft conversion. Wood fibre insulation, MVHR, airtightness layer, triple glazing, timber structure and low embodied energy materials.

name: 1.20 Oxo Tower Wharf
description: Unit 1.20 is one of 25 workshop and retail units in Oxo Tower Wharf and overlooks the courtyard towards the Bargehouse building from the first floor walkway. It is a multi-purpose space used as a workshop, showroom and teaching space.
address: Unit 1.20, The Courtyard, Oxo Tower Wharf, Bargehouse Street

name: 137 A Evering Road
description: The building is a set of four flats. Ours is Flat A in the basement. It has a unique interior and a long narrow garden.

name: 195 Mare Street
description: 195 Mare Street

name: 215 Mare Street
description: Morris+Company moved to Hackney in September 2022, a year in occupation and in collaboration with the 215 Mare St residents, it will open doors to the community and the wider public, featuring exhibitions, workshops and tours of the studios

name: 28 Lawrence Road, N15 4EG
description: The building serves as a live-and-work site for creatives, as well as our organisation, which plays an important role in the local community's life. We have two offices here, along with our Community Hub, which was designed by studio Unit38

name: 3 Arbuthnot Road
description: Open day / weekend of a contemporary house extension within a conservation area. The build was completed in 2022.

name: 4 Bayer House
description: Part of Golden Lane Estate which was the first public housing to be listed. A maisonette with much of the original detailing and finishes.

name: 6 Wood Lane
description: A double-height ark floats above a masonry base & entrance footbridge.  Off the elevated living area a smokers' balcony overlooks the lush garden below. Above, semi circular terrace and winter garden nestles within the wooded surrounds.

name: 8 Stoneleigh Terrace (Highgate New Town, Stage 1)
description: Built during the golden era of Camden public housing under Borough Architect Sydney Cook. Peter Tábori  studied with Ernő Goldfinger and worked with Denys Lasdun, and met Ken Adie when both were students at the Regent Street Polytechnic.

name: A Ruskinian Walk Through Shared Heritage
description: Ruskinian walk from RIBA award-winning Chiswick Business Park, Gunnersbury Triangle Nature Reserve through South Acton Estate, birthplace of artist Patrick Caulfield; Woodlands Park Ice House; to home of Wm Willett, of Daylight Saving Time
address: Building 3, Chiswick Business Park, 566 Chiswick High Road, W4 5YA

name: A3: Design District
description: Building A3 by Adam Khan Architects with its sturdy, geometric concrete exterior, can be seen as a nod to the aesthetics of raw construction found on emerging sites across the evolving Greenwich Peninsula.
address: Building A3 Design District, Soames Walk, SE10 0BJ

name: A4 & B4: Design District
description: A pair of affordable studio buildings as part of a new creative district on the Greenwich peninsula. David Kohn Architects worked with developer Knight Dragon on two new build creative studio buildings as part of the Design District.
address: The Gateway Pavilions, Peninsula Square, SE10 0QE

name: Abbey Mills Pumping Station
description:
Abbey Mills pumping station 'A', built by engineer Joseph Bazalgette, Edmund Cooper and architect Charles Driver. Built between 1865 and 1868 it is described as the cathedral of sewage.
Follow this link to book: https://bit.ly/abbeymills

name: Addington Village to Upper Shirley
description: Stroll from Addington Village to Upper Shirley to hear about ancient roads, buildings of former local trades, the medieval St. Mary's Church,  Addington Palace, post-war urban planning and a nursing home updated for the 21st century.
address: St. Mary's Church, Addington Village Road, Croydon, CR0 5AU

name: Alexandra Road Estate Flat 85B (Rowley Way)
description: Visit a recently refurbished apartments of Neave Brown’s Alexandra Road Estate in Camden. This is a 3 bed maisonette flat, lower ground and ground floor levels on block B along the pedestrian Rowley Way.

name: All Saints Church
description:
Historical connections
Admiral Fitzroy sailed to Galapagos Islands with Charles Darwin.
Grave within Church grounds.
Famous artist Camille Pissarro painted local scenes one of All Saints Church.
address: All Saints Church, Church Road, SE19 3EP

name: All Saints Church, Edmonton
description: Church dating back to at least early C12. Charles and Mary Lamb are buried in the churchyard.
address: All Saints Church, Church Street, N9 9AT

name: Ancient Livery Companies in the City of London
description:
On this walk we shall discover some of the livery companies, learn about their ancient traditions and ceremonies, which are repeated every year. Also hear about  their important role in the City.
Free walks led by City of London Guides

name: Anise Gallery- The Old Chapel
description: Located inside a fully renovated 1800s Zionist Chapel in Forest Hill, Anise Gallery will be open to the public to admire and see our completed space at The Old Chapel. There will be kids arts workshops, an exhibition and artwork sale.

name: Applecart Arts
description: Applecart Arts moved into the building and began an extensive refurbishment, opening the site to the public as a creative arts hub. The site now provides a home for a theatre, cafe, exhibition, rehearsal, and artist studio spaces.

name: Artist Performances on The Line
description: Join The Line for an afternoon of artist performances that respond to the local landscape, including a performance lecture by Simon Faithfull at Cody Dock and a site-specific performance by Helen Cammock at the House Mill.

name: BAPS Shri Swaminarayan Mandir
description: Europe’s first traditional Hindu temple is a masterpiece of exquisite Indian craftsmanship. Using 5,000 tonnes of Italian and Indian marble and the finest Bulgarian limestone, it was hand-carved in India before being assembled in London.

name: Baitul Futuh Mosque
description: Guided tours of the largest purpose-built mosque in Western Europe accommodating 13,000 worshippers blending of Islamic and modern British architecture. Recent developments, involving reconstruction after a fire, are nearing completion.
address: Ahmadiyya Muslim Association, 181 London Road, Morden, SM4 5PT

name: Balin House Projects
description:
BalinHouseProjects is an artist-run space and home.
It has published books about its activities over sixteen years.
The refurbishment was a collaboration with architect Torange Khonsari of public works and carpenter Matthias Bruene.
address: Flat 22, Balin House, Long Lane, SE1 1YQ

name: Beck Road Studios: Open Studios Exhibitions
description: Explore a vibrant artist community beneath a railway arch at our open studios! Engage with talented artists, discover diverse exhibitions. Join us in celebrating the creativity and sense of togetherness that define this unique space.

name: Benjamin Franklin House
description: Grade I listed Georgian house, the only surviving home of Benjamin Franklin, retaining many original features including central staircase, lathing, 18th Century panelling, stoves, windows, fittings and beams.

name: Blackhorse Workshop
description: A makerspace offering open access to a fully equipped wood and metal workshop with bench space, tools and machinery. Includes education space, community café and 40 studios for creative businesses.
address: Blackhorse Workshop, 1-2 Sutherland Road Path, E17 6BX

name: Bloqs
description: Bloqs is the UK's first open-access factory providing flexible and affordable access to industrial machinery, workshops and training with cafe / exhibition space and events venue. Winner of 3 architectural awards in 2023 from RIBA and AJ. This project is supported by the Mayor of London.

name: Bridget Riley studios
description: See behind the scenes of working studios that are not usually open to the public. Discover work by some of the UK’s top artists, from internationally acclaimed names to new and emerging talent.

name: Britannia Works studios
description: See behind the scenes of working studios that are not usually open to the public. Discover work by some of the UK’s top artists, from internationally acclaimed names to new and emerging talent.

name: Bruce Castle Museum
description: Tudor Manor House built for Sir William Compton in 1514, substantially altered in 17C, 18C & 19C. A museum since 1906 housing local history and community collections, archives, art & exhibitions of Bruce Castle, and Haringey area.
address: Bruce Castle Museum,, Lordship Lane, Tottenham, N17 8NU

name: Bruno Court, The German Hospital
description: Modernist extension to Hackney's German Hospital, closed 1987 and converted into flats in 1999.

name: Buzz Bingo Hall (former Granada Cinema)
description: Exceptional example of the 'luxury cinema style' of the 1930s with outstanding Gothic interior by Theodore Komisarjevsky. The first Grade I listed cinema. Visitors must be aged over 18.

name: C2 Clod Ensemble Studios : Design District
description: The building, designed by Mole Architects, comprises a 2000 square foot rehearsal top-lit studio, open-plan office, music production studio. Constructed entirely from timber, clad in weathered steel and designed to limit energy consumption.
address: C2 Cripps Yard, Soames Walk, Design District, SE10 0BQ

name: C3 : Bureau Design at District
description: C3 is home to Bureau, a members club at the heart of Design District. Its undulating white facade creates informal pockets of space on the interior, ideal for flexible working models.

name: CUFOS - Community Use For the Old Station
description: The former Alexandra Palace Railway Station now run by a charity for use by local people and organisations for classes, meetings and many other leisure activities.
address: CUFOS, Top of The Avenue, Muswell Hill, N10 2QE

name: Cannizaro Studios
description:
Victorian Potting sheds converted to artists' studios set within the grounds of Grade II listed Cannizaro Park.
The eight resident artists will be displaying their work during the festival at these unique studios.
address: The Old Potting Sheds, Cannizaro Park, SW19 4UW

name: Carshalton Water Tower and Historic Gardens
description: Early 18C Grade II listed building incorporating plunge bath with Delft tiles, orangery, saloon and pump chamber with part-restored water wheel. Hermitage and sham bridge in grounds.

name: Central Hill Estate
description: Tree-lined housing estate on the ridge of Central Hill & Crystal Palace, incorporating open spaces, views over London, gardens and sense of community. Rosemary Stjernstedt Ted Hollamby Adrian Sansom, Lambeth Borough Architects 1963.
address: Central Hill Bowl (behind Gipsy Hill Police Station) next to Mural /

name: Central Park, War Memorial and Cafe
description: The park opened in 1898. 7,000 attended the event, enjoying refreshments and speeches stressing the importance of creating resources for children. The walkways, fountain, bowling green, war memorial and cafe were incorporated over time.

name: Chart Street Studios
description: The redevelopment of a former furniture warehouse in Hackney. Using CLT and glulam, the existing building has been extended to include a new building over the yard as well as a new office space on the top floor of the main building.

name: Christ Church
description: Grade II* listed church with ragstone tower, spire, good stained glass by Kempe and recently restored William Hill organ. A characteristic work of Scott. It is Gothic Revival in the style of the 13C.

name: Christ Church Southgate and the Minchenden Oak Garden
description: Grade II listed church with fine collection of Pre-Raphaelite stained glass windows by Morris & Co. including Burne Jones and Rossetti. Wall paintings. Mosaic reredos. Minchenden Oak  - ancient pollarded oak more than 800 years old.

name: City Information Centre
description: London's main tourist information centre is clad in a specially manufactured system of 220 pre-finished stainless steel panels. The subtly reflective surface provides a striking counterpoint to St Paul's.

name: Cody Dock - Lea Way Celebration
description: Our event will focus on celebrating the rich heritage of Cody Dock, one of the last remaining brick-lined docks in London.  Our one-day festival will provide exciting opportunities to explore the lesser-known history of the Lower Lea Valley

name: Colour Casing
description: Awarded best project under £100k by Don’t Move Improve, Colour Casing creates the flexibility of a house within the footprint of an original small flat with a new rear and side addition.

name: Connected capital:  London's communication architecture
description: Join me on a walk through the architecture of entertainment and mass communication, exploring the stories behind a diverse range of iconic buildings and their role in asserting London's status as a globally connected, cultural powerhouse.

name: Crawley Road Studios
description: Crawley Road Open Studios, Tottenham Boutique and Makers Market and Turning Earth Ceramics Market, gourmet street food led by resident chefs Bolland and Crust, art exhibition and a wide range of making demonstrations and family activities.
address: Crawley Road Studios, 38 Crawley Road, N22 6QS

name: Crystal Palace Park Trust - Garden Party
description: On Sunday 17th September, we celebrate the historic takeover of Crystal Palace Park by the charitable, community-led Crystal Palace Park Trust.  Join us for the Garden Party: a free festival of music, markets, makers and merriment!

name: Cut Glass Studio Ltd, Tottenham Hale
description: Unit used as an art studio in a small industrial estate.
address: 15-16 The High Cross Centre, Fountayne Road, N15 4QN

name: D1 & C1: Bureau at Design District
description: Building D1, designed by Architecture 00 forms one of two buildings that house Bureau, which offers coworking in the heart of Design District. D1 is home to a variety of workspaces and businesses with meeting rooms, studios and Forum.

name: D4 : Design District
description:
D4 overlooks central square with a tall and slim facade acting as a landmark feature within
the district.
address: Building D4, Design District, Dormer Yard, 5-6 Soames Walk, SE10 0AX

name: DEEP SPACE
description: New build live/ work unit, unique architecture in a quiet mews in Brockley.

name: Design District Public Realm
description: Design District is a collection of 16 buildings designed by eight architects, one minute from North Greenwich station. The District supports an ecosystem of creative businesses and helps foster connections through affordable spaces, comprehensive facilities and a thriving events programme.
address: The Gateway Pavilions, Peninsula Square, SE10 0QE

name: Devonport Mausoleum
description: Beautiful mausoleum in former Royal Navy cemetery, restored 1999 by the University of Greenwich. Many interesting plaques and grave stones.

name: Drapers' Hall
description: Livery hall first built in the 1530s, twice destroyed by fire and rebuilt (1666 & 1772). Late 19C facade and opulent Victorian interior.

name: Dulwich College
description: Barry Buildings: 1869. Grade II* listed. Palladian symmetrical plan, in terracotta and stone. Extensively refurbished 2017-2018. New Science Building 2016. Grimshaw Architects. RIBA National Award. Home to 'James Caird' boat.

name: Eames Fine Art
description: A great example of the rich evolution of London’s buildings; from noxious leather treatment warehouse complete with sloping floors, winch poles and loading platforms to a stylish hidden Art Collector’s Studio in the space of 150 years.

name: Eastbury Manor House
description: Architecturally distinguished and well-preserved, brick-built, Elizabethan Grade I listed manor house. Contains 17C wall-paintings, wood panelling, a charming walled garden and a fine Tudor turret. Many original features have been restored.
address: Eastbury Manor House, Eastbury Square, Barking, IG11 9SN

name: Emery Walker's House
description: The home of Emery Walker, printer, antiquary and mentor to William Morris. A unique Arts and Crafts domestic interior.

name: Epping Forest Visitor Centre at Chingford, The View
description: Epping Forest Visitor Centre at Chingford, The View, a visitor centre and museum, was created from an early 20C stable complex. Enjoy its Forest viewing balcony, exhibitions and unique status as gateway into 6000 acres of Forest trails.

name: Estorick Collection of Modern Italian Art
description: The Estorick Collection is housed in a beautiful Georgian building previously known as Northampton Lodge. Today, the museum comprises six galleries over three floors, as well as a library, offices, a café and bookshop.

name: Firepit Studios: Exhibition
description: Firepit is an artist run collective. The collective's purpose is to create a safe inclusive space for artists to work and for people to visit. There will be ten multi-media artists exhibiting at Firepit during Open House to enjoy.
address: Firepit, Ground floor unit 5, 10 Cutter Lane, SE10 0XX

name: Fleet Street Heritage Information Project and Sundial
description: This new sundial faces East so gets only morning sun. It is 10 m. square and was opened in 2021, and is publicly accessible 24/7

name: Forty Hall Estate
description: This Grade I listed Jacobean Manor House is set in a fine estate. Built by Sir Nicholas Rainton, Lord Mayor of London 1632-33, as a family home, it is presented as a multi period House with interesting features from different centuries.

name: Foster + Partners
description: We're excited to open up our London campus as part of Open House Festival. Foster + Partners is a global studio for sustainable architecture, urbanism, engineering and design, founded by Norman Foster in 1967. With offices across the world, the practice works as a single entity that is both ethnically and culturally diverse, with people central to all our endeavours.

name: From Forest to Morris: A walk around Walthamstow
description: A walk around historic Walthamstow showing how this unique area grew from a village into a thriving suburb, its social history and the variety of buildings that can be found where Epping Forest meets William Morris.
address: Outside Costa Coffee at Walthamstow Central Station 5 Station Approac

name: Fruit to Fashion: how a kitchen garden became a world famous piazza
description: The tour charts the evolution of Covent Garden-incorporating the piazza, the wholesale produce market, social residential areas and supporting neighbourhoods - highlighting the social and commercial highs, lows and challenges.

name: Fulham Palace
description: Early Tudor Palace with Georgian reception rooms, Victorian Chapel, 13 acres of botanic gardens and walled garden.

name: GOOD FOOD MATTERS - CHOOSE LOVE GARDEN
description: come and visit the charity GOOD FOOD MATTERS and see our amazing teaching kitchen, cedar clad award winning sustainable co building, food growing space, orchards and THE CHOOSE LOVE GARDEN all her in Croydon , your City of Culture for 2023.
address: The Community Food Learning Center, Mickleham Way, Croydon, CR0 0PN

name: Gap House
description:
Tours of Gap House
Just 8ft wide to the street, this house is ingeniously slotted into an unpromising plot to create a comfortable, low energy, family home that makes a virtue of its constrained site.

name: Garden Court Chambers
description: Inigo Jones design 1640 at 59/60 LIF, copied  by 57/58  with portico and elliptical staircase added by Soane.  Refurbished by current occupiers, a barristers' chambers. Retains many original features, staircases, fireplaces and mouldings

name: Garrick's Temple to Shakespeare, Hampton
description: Grade I listed Georgian garden building. Tribute to Shakespeare built in the Ionic style by actor David Garrick. Arcadian Thames-side setting in restored 18C gardens thought to be by Capability Brown.
address: Garrick's Lawn, Hampton Court Road, , Hampton, TW12 2EN

name: Golders Green Quaker Meeting House
description: Delightful brick and tile building inspired by the famous 1688 Meeting House at Jordans in Buckinghamshire. A simple building in a tranquil setting, reflecting the Quakers' beliefs.

name: Greenside Primary School
description: One of only two primary schools designed by Erno Goldfinger using a pre-cast concrete system - an important modernist building. The building is Grade II* listed and has a fine top-lit mural in the foyer, commissioned by Goldfinger and designed and painted by Gordon Cullen, recently re-restored.  The schoolkeeper's cottage has recently been refurbished and brought into the daily life of the school.

name: Guildhall
description: The City's seat of municipal government since 12C. Grade I listed, rare example of medieval civic architecture.

name: Guildhall Art Gallery
description:
UPDATED: Open daily 10.30am-4pm. 
Guided tours 12.15pm & 1.15pm on Tuesdays, Thursdays, Fridays, Saturdays & Sundays, see below.
Home of the City of London's art collection, & remains of London's Roman Amphitheatre

name: HG Wells' Bromley - in his own words
description: A walk around the streets that the young Herbert George Wells knew when he was growing up and wrote about in his autobiography. You will get a flavour of Bromley in its Victorian heyday - all in the words of the author of the 'Time Machine'

name: Hackney Empire
description: Hackney Empire is a grade II* listed building. The theatre was built as a music hall in 1901, designed by the architect Frank Matcham. It is now an exceptional variety theatre for the 21st century, serving the local community and beyond.

name: Havant House 53
description: A victorian mid terrace house with a dark blue exterior and a zany tiled front garden. Full of original features without being dictated by the era, colour continues inside with a yellow rubber floor in the kitchen.

name: Heritage on the High Road (High Street HAZ)
description: Hear about some of the initiatives under way in the Tottenham High Street Heritage Action Zone (High Street HAZ). LB Haringey and the Tottenham Civic Society host a tour uncovering the rich heritage of this bustling, multicultural area.
address: Bruce Grove Public Conveniences, Bruce Grove, N17 6UR

name: Historic & Modern Buildings in the City
description:
On this walk we will see many historic & modern buildings. see different architecture styles having regard to the environment and sustainability, and hear about famous architects, past and present.

Free walks led by City of London Guides

name: Historic Bromley Town Exhibition
description: An Exhibition celebrating the historic character and heritage of Bromley from its origins as a Kentish market town through the Victorian Golden Age to the present time with many buildings in the Arts and Crafts style that can be seen today.
address: Lower Mall, The Glades shopping centre, 64 High Street, Bromley

name: Holy Cross Church, Cromer Street
description: Grade ll listed Oxford Movement Anglican church built 1887-88. Historic England describe the exterior as ‘quirky and aggressive’ but the  interior is ‘very spare and elegant, the proportions subtly adjusted’. Elevated choir and sanctuary.

name: Holy Trinity Church Sloane Square
description: A sumptuous feast of Victorian stained glass & bold sacred sculpture in what Sir John Betjeman called the 'cathedral of the Arts and Crafts movement.' Work by William Morris, Edward Burne-Jones, William Blake- Richmond & Christopher Whall.
address: 146 Sloane Street (just off Sloane Square), SW1X 9BZ

name: Homes for working women walking tour
description: Hampstead Garden Suburb was a planned community for all classes, including a growing number of single working women. On this walk we will explore the variety of housing designed specifically for women including communal living and training facilities.
address: Parking area adjacent to Golders Hill Park Cafe, North End Way

name: House Mill
description: The World’s largest tidal mill. 5-storey, timber-framed, brick-clad timber watermill with four waterwheels, originally built 1776 to mill grain for distillery trade. Operational until 1940. On historic 3 Mills Site, Clock Mill adjacent.
address: Three Mill Lane, Bromley by Bow , E3 3DU

name: House extension in Stoke Newington
description: A contextual extension of a Victorian house that redefines the inside-outside connection. The inside features selected framed views of the garden, and cherry joinery that contrasts with the stainless steel kitchen and concrete floor.

name: Inner Temple Gardens
description: Established by the Knights Templar in 1195, The Inner Temple has had a Gardener since 1307. Surviving The Great Fire of London, and the Blitz, the Gardens remain a secret tranquil oasis in heart of the city.
address: The Inner Temple Gardens, Crown Office Row, EC4Y 7BS

name: Isokon Building (Lawn Road Flats)
description: Grade I listed 1934 residential block of flats in Hampstead, designed by the Canadian modernist architect Wells Coates for clients Jack and Molly Pritchard. English Heritage blue plaque for Bauhaus masters Gropius, Breuer and Moholy-Nagy.

name: Jerram Falkus Construction Ltd
description: Based in Shoreditch since the start of the centaury and still family owned, Jerram Falkus would like to open its office doors, for visitors to see our unique garden and sympathetically refurbished offices, along with history of the company

name: John Grindrod: Polaroids of Croydon
description: Join John Grindrod, author of 'Iconicon' and 'Concretopia', on a walk around the endless rebuilding of Croydon town centre.
address: One Croydon, 12–16 Addiscombe Rd, Croydon, CR0 6SD

name: Kaymet Factory
description: The operational factory of Kaymet, a maker of trays and trolleys since 1947. A hidden 1950s building with a small yard, originally a printing works. It is brick built, with clear-storey glazing and tubular truss north-light main shed roof.

name: Keats House
description: Keats House is the beautiful Regency villa, where Romantic poet John Keats found inspiration, friendship and love. Today, it is a museum provided by the City of London Corporation for the benefit of London and the nation.

name: King's College London, The Maughan Library
description: London's first fireproof building, built to house records of the Court of Chancery. Now renovated to house a fine university library.

name: Kingswood House
description: Grade II listed building. Substantial villa built in form of stone-faced baronial castle for the inventor of Bovril. An internal refurbishment is planned to convert it into a cultural and community space.

name: Kitchen in the Woods
description:
Winner of the  Urban Oasis awards of Don't Move Improve 2023! with an extension by A Small Studio architects.

This is an Austin Vernon & Partners 1957 home that sits within the Dulwich Estate.

name: Lavender Hill Chapel
description: The building is a Grade II non-conformist cemetery chapel, designed by T J Hill for the Enfield Burial Board in 1870-71 in the Decorated Gothic style.

name: Lea Bridge Library
description: Studio Weave were commissioned to design an extension to the Grade-II listed Lea Bridge Library in East London, adding a cafe and adaptable community space – to deliver a revived civic heart for the Borough of Waltham Forest. This project is supported by the Mayor of London.

name: Lewisham Homes presents: The Pepys Estate, High Up
description: Visit the Pepys Estate, a 1960s social housing estate built by the Greater London Council. You will be able to visit the top of a residential tower (one of the tallest buildings in London when built) and hear about local community projects.
address: 2000 Community Action Centre, 199-201 Grove Street, SE8 3PG

name: Leyton House
description: Leyton House is a new build house that has been designed to maximise the potential of its urban infill setting.

name: Little Angel Theatre
description: Little Angel Theatre was converted from a derelict temperance hall in 1961 and has been showcasing puppetry performances ever since. It is London's only purpose-built puppet theatre, due to the existence of its marionette bridge.

name: Little Brownings
description: My midcentury terraced house on the Dulwich Estate was the  overall winner of last year's Don't Move Improve. My architects Archmongers will be here too to talk people through the design/build. (Approached to apply by Prudence Ivey)

name: Little Mouse Cheese Shop
description: Visit Little Mouse, an Edwardian shop in South Norwood with original wooden frontage and fascia that is now an artisan cheesemonger.

name: London Open Form Pavilion of Air
description: A floating roof of sound, GPS-triggered & accessed by headphones & Echoes app to playfully reframe public space as an essential community engagement. One of 15 in an international series drawing on Oskar & Zofia Hansen’s Open Form concept.

name: London's Roman Amphitheatre
description:
UPDATED: Open daily 10.30am-4pm Closed Mon 19 September.
Combined guided tours of Amphitheatre and Guildhall Art Gallery at 12.15pm & 1.15pm on Tuesdays, Thursdays, Fridays, Saturdays & Sundays.
The capital’s only known Roman Amphitheatre
address: London’s Roman Amphitheatre at Guildhall Art Gallery, Guildhall Yard

name: Mansion House
description: The official residence of the Lord Mayor of the City of London, retaining its 18C character, with superb plasterwork and wood carving.

name: Mark Masons' Hall
description: This Victorian building is situated next door to St James' Palace. Fronted in stone in a 'Grosvenor Hotel' Italianate style, coarse foliage ornamentation adorns the facade with grand interiors adapted for Masonic use in the 1970s.

name: Museum of London Docklands
description: Grade I listed, late Georgian sugar warehouse now housing the Museum of London Docklands. Sensitively restored, the new multimedia displays coexist with the massive timber and brick structures of the original building.
address: No. 1 Warehouse, West India Quay (off Hertsmere Road), E14 4AL

name: NOW Gallery : Design District
description: The NOW Gallery is an art space - contained within two curved glass pavilions linked by a patinated brass-edged canopy - which defines the southern edge of Peninsula Square and acts as a gateway to the south, the cable car and Central Park.
address: The Gateway Pavilions, Peninsula Square, Greenwich Peninsula

name: Nag's Head Market
description: Nag's Head Market has occupied its current site since 1975, and it has recently been overhauled by Office S&M to support its diverse traders that cater for the local community.

name: National Maritime Museum
description: We are aiming to do four free guided tours that are normally paid with which we can offer max up to 25 people on each. We will also have drop in talks run by the Visitor and Sales team on specific subjects for people to drop into.

name: National Portrait Gallery Architecture Highlights Tours
description: Discover the architecture of the National Portrait Gallery, designed in 1896 by Ewan Christian and now transformed by Jamie Fobert Architects. Please meet at the Ross Street Entrance. Drop-in 16 & 17 September at specific times listed below.  But please note that spaces are extremely limited and tour places will be allocated on a first come, first served basis. Please arrive early to avoid disappointment.
address: National Portrait Gallery, St Martin's Place, WC2H 0HE

name: Oak Room, New River Head
description: Formerly boardroom of the 17C water house, the Oak Room is a fine late Renaissance room demonstrating the New River Company's wealth. Booking link: https://bit.ly/OakRooms
address: New River Head, , 173 Rosebery Avenue, EC1R 4UL

name: Old Royal Naval College - King William Court
description: Wren-designed building completed under the direction of Hawksmoor and Vanbrugh, 1698-1712. Original wood panelling, refurbished by Dannatt Johnson in 2001 for University of Greenwich.
address: King William Court, 30 Park Row, SE10 9NN

name: Old Royal Naval College - Queen Anne Court
description: Wren and Hawksmoor building, completed 1749 when Thomas Ripley built the pavilions facing the river. Highlights include council boardroom, grand staircase and restored Portland stonework. Refurbished in 2000 for University of Greenwich.
address: Queen Anne Court , 30 Park Row, SE10 9NN

name: Old Royal Naval College - Queen Mary Court
description: Last major building on the site (1751). Original layout, timber panelling, barrel vaulting and Portland stone. Refurbished in 2000 by Dannatt Johnson for University of Greenwich.
address: Queen Mary Court, 30 Park Row, SE10 9NN

name: Olympic Legacy Masterplan
description: London’s 2012 Games provided a catalyst for regeneration in the Lower Lea Valley. Guided by the Legacy Masterplan, thousands of new homes and jobs are now being created, stitching together existing communities across the former floodplain.

name: Paxton Locher House
description: A unique modern courtyard house making brilliant use of a restricted site. A retractable glass roof gives wonderful natural light and opens the house to the sky in dry weather.

name: Peter Cushing House
description: 1920s Art Deco house, formerly the home of Peter Cushing OBE. English Heritage Blue Plaque.

name: Public art trail: Portraits of the South
description:
Public art trail: Portraits of the South by Abi Partington-Moran 

This innovative artist-created trail in Sutton Town Centre is the first of four Sutton STEAMS Ahead photographic commissions to be unveiled this Autumn/Winter.

name: Queen Elizabeth's Hunting Lodge
description: Tudor timber-framed hunt standing/grandstand (1543),  Henry VIII Tudor food display. Gateway to 6,000 acres ancient Epping Forest, once royal hunting ground, protected since 1878 by City of London, Grade II*.  Epping Forest visitor Centre.

name: RC Church of St Mellitus
description: A grand neo-classical building of 1871 with impressive interior, built as New Court Congregational Chapel. Home to a Hunter pipe organ, installed as a WW1 memorial and recently restored with National Lottery Heritage Fund support.
address: St Mellitus RC Church, Tollington Park, N4 3AG

name: RSA (Royal Society for the encouragement of Arts, Manufactures and Commerce)
description: A very good example of Georgian/Adam architecture. Restoration 2012 of Great Room (James Barry paintings), Benjamin Franklin room. 2019, restoration and installation of 1754-2018 mural in the new Long Gallery.

name: Radical women of Bow and Bethnal Green
description: This walking tour will celebrate the women of Bow and Bethnal Green – from the match makers of the Bryant and May factory to the Quinn Square rent strikers – looking at how, through their activism, they were able to change the built environment.
address: Underneath the blue plaque outside Bow Quarter ( the old Bryant and M

name: Reform Club
description: Built as a Whig gentleman's club and inspired by Italian Renaissance palaces. Lobby leads to an enclosed colonnaded courtyard with complementary glazed roof and tessellated floor. Tunnelled staircase leads to upper floor.

name: Round Chapel
description: Grade II* listed Nonconformist chapel for 1,000 people. Described by Pevsner as 'one of the finest Nonconformist buildings in London'. Horseshoe plan, innovative cast-iron columns and tracery, restored as a centre for the performing arts.
address: Lower Clapton Road (junction with Glenarm Road), E5 0NP

name: Royal College of General Practitioners
description: Grade II* listed building. Restored in 2012 to showcase magnificent Edwardian faience tile work, mosaic floor and other historic features in transformed modern surroundings that now provide the headquarters of the RCGP.

name: Royal Hospital Chelsea, Home of the Chelsea Pensioners
description:
Numbered amongst the UK's architectural glories and boasting 66 acres of beautiful grounds, the Royal Hospital Chelsea has been home to the iconic Army veteran community fondly known as the 'Chelsea Pensioners' since its foundation in 1692. 
The Great Hall and Chapel will not be accessible from 12.00-14.00 on Saturday 16th September due to an internal event. The remainder of the site will be open during this time. 

Visitors should note that filming will be taking place during the afternoon of Sunday 17th September. If you would like to be excluded from any filming, please let our staff and volunteers know on arrival at the site.

name: Royal School of Needlework
description: Baroque palace built for King William III and Mary II. The original Tudor towers and chimneys were replaced by grand and elegant exteriors that dominate the buildings today.
address: RSN Shop, East Front Gardens, Hampton Court Palace, KT8 9AU

name: Rufford Mews Apartment
description: The interior of this property has been designed by Mike McMahon and the majority of the furniture and cabinetry have been made by Mike & Jewlsy over the course of a number of years including lighting, chairs, sofas, beds etc.

name: Saddlers' Hall
description: Home of the Worshipful Company of Saddlers, Saddlers’ Hall is built in a neo-classical style and impresses with bespoke period furniture, historical antiquities, and paintings. The highlight is the Great Hall.

name: Sensing space in the City
description: This sensory walk explores the art of moving mindfully through urban space – focusing on the rhymes, rhythm, volumes, and voids that normally flow past unnoticed. We begin in Inner Temple and wander west to Somerset House, through Trafalgar Square, ending at the Royal Academy.
address: Tudor Street Gate, Middle Temple, EC4Y 0BH

name: Shirley Windmill
description: The present brick tower windmill was built 1854 to replace a post mill destroyed by fire. Now renovated to near-working condition, it is the only surviving windmill in Croydon.
address: Postmill Close, Upper Shirley Road, Croydon, CR0 5DY

name: Shoreditch Town Hall
description: Once one of the grandest civic buildings in London and now a great arts venue, the Grade II listed Shoreditch Town Hall boasts many spaces, from the Victorian grandeur of the Assembly Hall to the intimate warren of untouched basement rooms.
address: Shoreditch Town Hall, 380 Old Street, EC1V 9LT

name: Sir John Soane's Museum
description:
The extraordinary home of architect Sir John Soane (1753-1837). 

https://www.soane.org/whats-on

name: South London Theatre
description: Grade II listed 1881 former fire station with prominent watch tower and original fire doors.
address: The Old Fire Station, 2a Norwood High Street, SE27 9NS

name: Springbank
description: One of a pair of modern houses on a sensitive site in a conservation area. A triple-height staircase atrium brings light into the heart of the house and ground floor areas open onto courtyard gardens on three sides.

name: Squaring the Corners Activity Day + Tour
description: nimtim architects, with artist Katie Schwab, have reimagined four of Becontree’s existing corner plots, as a new public square for the community to meet, rest, play and grow. The square is the first space of its kind on the Estate.
address: Junction of Lindsey + Fuller Road, Dagenham, RM8 2TU

name: St Anne's Church, Limehouse
description: St Anne's Limehouse has been described as 'the finest parish church in England.' Designed by Nicholas Hawksmoor, it is Grade I listed and one of the Major Churches in the Church of England. It is home to a thriving Christian congregation.

name: St Augustine's Tower
description: Grade I listed, remaining tower of medieval parish church, with working late 16C clock. New exhibition of Hackney's history. Extensive views from roof. (Organised by Hackney Historic Buildings Trust).

name: St John on Bethnal Green
description: This grade one listed Sir John Soane church sits in the heart of the Bethnal Green in East London. Despite a fire in 1870, some original features remain. Visitors will have access to the church,  belfry, galleries and crypt.
address: St John on Bethnal Green, 200 Cambridge Heath Road, E2 9PA

name: St John the Evangelist, Upper Norwood
description: St John's is a Grade II* listed church, designed by John Loughborough Pearson

name: St Jude on the Hill
description: Eccentric Edwardian church, Grade I listed. Described by Simon Jenkins as 'one of Lutyens' most distinctive creations'. Extensive 20C wall-paintings by Walter Starmer, memorial to horses of WWI. Local archives display.

name: St Lawrence Church, Morden
description: Grade I listed Norman brick-built church consisting of a nave and chancel. Tower at the west end. Gothic-style stone windows from the old church inserted into the present 1636 structure. Rare 17th Century glass was restored in 2020.

name: St Mary The Virgin Wanstead
description: One of the finest examples of Georgian architecture. It has been hardly altered since built. The church is a rectangular building of Portland stone, with a projecting chancel. Two external walls were restored in 2019. Grade I listed
address: St Mary The Virgin Church , Overton Drive, E11 2LW

name: St Michael and All Angels Church
description: James Maltby Bignall (1827-1885) worked in the practice of Sir George Gilbert Scott, the architect of St Pancras Station. The style of St Michael's is late Gothic Revival, in its size and height reminiscent of Northern European churches.

name: St Nicholas Church, Chislehurst
description: Medieval Parish Church, 15C, enlarged & rebuilt in 19C. Shingle spire 1857, by Wollaston. Chancel by Ferrey, lengthened with East wall by Bodley & Garner. Scadbury Chapel (Walsingham tombs), with rood screen. Clock by Dent, 1858.

name: St Pancras Chambers and Clock Tower
description: Former Midland Grand Hotel, now St Pancras Renaissance Hotel and Chambers apartments. Includes hotel lobby and clock tower.
address: The Forecourt, St Pancras Station, Euston Road, NW1 2AR

name: St Paul's Bow Common
description: Described as 'the most significant church built after the WWII in Britain' - Brutalist, inclusive and influential signpost for future church design.
address: Corner of Burdett Road/ St Paul's Way, E3 4AR

name: St Paul's, Newington
description: Modern architecture church with large copper and lead roof and concrete, brick and stained glass external structure. Marble, wood and plaster interior and artwork by Sculptor Freda Pinto and Gerald Holtom.

name: St Peter & St Paul Harlington
description: Grade I listed church dating from 1086, representing the architectural styles of many centuries, including Norman font and carved cats heads around Norman south doorway arch, Easter sepulchre and ancient yew tree in churchyard.
address: St Peter's Way, High Street, Harlington, UB3 5AB

name: St Peter Church Petersham
address: Church Lane, off The Petersham Road, Richmond, TW10 7AB

name: St. Mary's Church, Walthamstow Village
description: Grade II* listed church dating from 12C with Medieval, Tudor, Georgian & Victorian features. 16C Tower. Church refurbishment and new extension in progress in 2022. Over 1300 monuments with four Grade II listed tombs in churchyard.
address: Church End (top of Church Hill), Walthamstow, E17 9RJ

name: Surbiton Queen of the Suburbs
description:
Join us for an interesting and informative walk around Surbiton with our experienced guide. Find out why Surbiton was called the Queen of the suburbs and plenty more. 

Visit our website: https://www.kingstontourguides.org.uk/

name: Taylor & Chatto Courts and Wilmott Court, Frampton Park Estate
description: Taylor Court and Chatto Court, together with Wilmott Court, form a pair of award-winning mixed-tenure housing, accommodating 45 new homes and commissioned by the Hackney Council on two sites at the edge of the post-war Frampton Park Estate.

name: Temple Bar
description: Temple Bar is a 350 year old gateway to the City of London, designed by Sir Christopher Wren. It formerly stood in Fleet Street, and was the last surviving gateway to the City of London.
address: First Floor, Paternoster Lodge, 2 Paternoster Square, EC4M 7DX

name: Thames River Police
description: A unique ex-carpenters' workshop (1910), contained within a working police station. The workshop space now displays a history of Thames River Police.

name: The Africa Centre
description: A 1960s former office block that has been transformed into a vibrant cultural hub showcasing the best of contemporary African culture and heritage. This project is supported by the Mayor of London.

name: The Banqueting House
description: Stunning regal building, the only surviving building from Whitehall Palace, one of the first examples of the principles of Palladianism being applied to an English building. Site of a set of magnificent ceiling paintings by Rubens.

name: The Barbican & The City Gardens
description: Built on the site destroyed by The Blitz during the World War II, The Barbican Estate is a fascinating area and an icon of Brutalist architecture. Architects were Chamberlain, Powell and Bon,  We  will also visit several amazing gardens.

name: The Caledonian Club
description: Built in Neoclassical style for Hugh Morrison (1868-1931), this was the last mansion house of its kind to be built in London. The club, founded in 1891, moved to the premises in 1946.

name: The Chapel in Tottenham Cemetery
description: Two York stone Chapels are linked by a carriage arch built from Kentish Ragstone. The exterior is symmetrical and sturdy but the interior is a light stained glass spacious sanctuary with original features that make you step back in time.

name: The Church of St Mary's and new community centre
description: The Church was built in 1874 by R.J Withers. The adjoining building was remodeled by Goodhart Rendell in the 1920s Arts and Crafts style. The Pineapple Project for community use, by Matthew Lloyd Architects, was completed this year.
address: The Church of St Mary's Bourne Street, Westminster, SW1W 8JJ

name: The Fleet beneath your feet
description: A walk along and around a stretch of London's most famous hidden river. The River Fleet is underground these days, but it's left its mark on the landscape. Discover the layers of history in this less explored corner of central London.

name: The Gilbert & George Centre
description: The Gilbert & George Centre was originally established as a registered charity by the artist in 2009 with the objective to advance the education of the public in the arts, and generally to advance the arts, architecture, heritage and culture for the benefit of the public.

name: The Great Fire of London
description:
In 1666, the conflagration devastated most of the City, thousands of houses, many churches and St Paul's Cathedral destroyed. Christopher Wren played a major role in rebuilding the City. 
Free walks led by City of London Guides

name: The Honourable Society of the Middle Temple
description: We will be opening the Hall and Library of the  Middle Temple on the 17 September between 12 and 4pm for tours.
address: Middle Temple, Middle Temple Lane, London EC4Y 6BT, EC4Y 9BT

name: The Hospital Chapel of St Mary & St Thomas
description: Founded c1145 by the Abbess of Barking as a hospice for thirteen old and infirm men, the present building is 12C and 19C. Grade II* listed with many interesting monuments, including Burne-Jones windows.

name: The Mildmay Club
description: A rare example of a large purpose built metropolitan working men’s club with over 100 years of history. A once dignified building, revival Queen Anne style in the late-Victorian period, Grade II listed in 2019.

name: The Old Deanery
description: This Grade I Mansion House, close to St Paul's Cathedral was designed by Edward Woodroofe in 1669 and completed in 1673.  The residence of successive Deans of St Pauls until the 1970's today it is the office to the Bishop of London
address: The Old Deanery, Deans Court, EC4V 5AA

name: The Old Palace, Bromley Civic Centre (The Bishop's Palace)
description: The Old Palace was the official residence of the Bishops of Rochester. Present building dates from 1775, although there have been manor houses on the site since 10C.
address: Civic Centre, Stockwell Close, Bromley, BR1 3UH

name: The Old Schoolhouse
description: Originally St, Mary's Infants School, later as Holy Innocents' National School until 1934. It then became derelict until 1981 when it became headquarters of the Hornsey Historical Society in 1981 after refurbishment.

name: The Queen's House
description: Home to an internationally renowned art collection, Inigo Jones’ architectural masterpiece is the first Classical building in the UK. Home to the largest collection of Maritime art and currently hosting an exhibition on the Van de Velde's.

name: The Rosemary Branch Theatre
description: The Rosemary Branch Theatre is a pub theatre located in Islington. Previously a Victorian Music Hall which once hosted the likes of famed Music Hall singer Marie Lloyd, it has a rich history in the London theatre community.

name: The Royal Arsenal - Then, Now and Into the Future
description: The Royal Arsenal was pivotal in every major conflict for over 400 years. After years of being off-limits, many buildings have been re-purposed as performing arts spaces, restaurants, bars and most recently a huge residential complex.
address: Woolwich station of Elizabeth line, Dial Arch Square

name: The Royal Society
description: A spectacular Grade I listed building designed by famed architect John Nash. Built in 1831, these former townhouses have undergone refurbishments throughout their history. The building is now home to the UK's national science academy.
address: The Royal Society, 6-9 Carlton House Terrace, SW1Y 5AG

name: The Temple Church
description: Medieval architecture meets Wren's refurbishments in this inspiring building, the Mother Church of the Common Law. The Magna Carta exhibit: has William Marshal and King John where they would have debated and agreed clauses of Magna Carta.

name: The Tin Tabernacle / Cambridge Hall
description:
Built 1863 - a large corrugated iron chapel. Inside was transformed after the last war into a battleship by local sailors for Sea Cadets. 
It has decks, portholes a Bofors Gun and alter from the set of the 1964 film Becket.

name: Thornhill Square
description: A tour of one of the largest and best preserved early Victorian squares and gardens in London, also with a magnificent and original public library of 1906, which shows Byzantine and Art Nouveau influences, and a remarkable Gothic church.
address: Meet outside the main door of St Andrew’s Church, Bridgeman Road

name: Timothy Hatton Architects – The Foundry
description: Tucked behind a busy road in W12, this former foundry is a multi-level development featuring an architects’ studio with courtyards and spaces for exhibitions and musical performances. The  building's 15m brick chimney is a local landmark.

name: Tower Gardens Garden Suburb
description: One of the first garden suburbs in the world, 2-storey terraced cottages retaining decorative architectural features. LCC created 'housing of the working classes' role for architects' department under Riley, member of the Art Workers guild.
address: 5 Tower Gardens Road, North Tottenham, N17 7PX

name: Tower Hamlets Town Hall
description: Tower Hamlets Town Hall, the new headquarters for the London Borough of Tower Hamlets Council, encompasses the restoration of the Grade II listed former Royal London Hospital building, and the addition of a new build extension.

name: Tower and Churchyard of St Mary's Hornsey
description: Grade II* listed tower with restored chapel remaining from Medieval parish church. Tour includes crypt, ringing chamber & main roof with excellent extensive views in all directions. Organised by Friends of Hornsey Church Tower.

name: Turning Earth Ceramics Tottenham N22
description: The new ceramics studio occupies the top floor of a beautiful old saw-toothed factory building within the Crawley Road industrial estate, one of several new creative businesses joining the area

name: Two Temple Place
description: Completed in 1895, Two Temple Place is a dazzling neo-Gothic gem on the Victoria Embankment, designed by gothic revivalist architect, John Loughborough Pearson, & commissioned by & built for William Waldorf Astor, as his estate office.

name: Two-up Two-down House
description: Two-Up Two-Down House is a reworking of a Victorian mid terrace by architects Khan Bonshek. They use imaginative spatial devices to maximise the limited floor area. Double height volumes & blurring of rooms combine to create space & light.

name: University of Chicago Booth School of Business
description: Chicago Booth's London campus combines the best of old and new. Located near St. Paul's, the campus features more than 50 pieces of contemporary art and houses our Executive MBA Programme Europe, Executive Education, and conference centre.
address: One Bartholomew Close, Barts Square, EC1A 7BL

name: University of Greenwich, Stockwell Street
description: The building features a limestone exterior designed to 'complement but not mimic' the surrounding historical architecture, whilst behind the façade is a 4-storey composition of steel, glass and exposed concrete.

name: University of Westminster
description: The University of Westminster was one of the first polytechnics in the UK. Founded in 1838 as the Royal Polytechnic Institution, it was established to educate the working people of London, regardless of background or financial status.

name: Valentines Mansion & Gardens
description: Large, late 17C Grade II* listed house with fine staircase and Venetian window and Georgian additions, used as a family dwelling until the early 1900s. Reopened to the public in Feb 2009 following extensive restoration works.

name: Van Gogh House London
description: The carefully renovated Van Gogh House seeks to share its story and inspire a new generation of artists through Van Gogh’s London story. The house curates a dynamic programme of events anchored in the artist’s practice and local heritage.

name: Walmer Yard
description: Forming a discreet and private set of four interlocking houses set around an open courtyard, Walmer Yard is Peter Salter's only UK project. The houses now form the home of the Baylight Foundation.

name: Walter Segal Self-build Houses
description: A close of 13 self-built houses. Each is unique, built using method developed by Walter Segal, who led the project in the 1980s. Houses have been extended and renovated. Sustainable features including solar electric, water & space heating.
address: Walters Way, Honor Oak Park , SE23 3LH

name: Waltham Forest Town Hall
description: Grade II listed Town Hall clad in Portland Stone. The building incorporates Art Deco and Nordic Classicism styles, also being influenced by the work of local activist William Morris. Extensively refurbished in 2019 by Hawkins Brown.
address: Waltham Forest Town Hall ,  Forest Road, E17 4JF

name: Walworth Garden
description: Our timber frame building was designed by Matrix Feminist Design Co-Operative, and built by women. It represents our community's history of activism-the same ethos that transformed our site from dereliction, into a thriving community garden

name: Wanstead Heritage Walk
description: A guided walk, Wanstead Station to The Temple, Wanstead Park, taking in Wanstead's history and architectural heritage .The walk finishes at The Temple and will include an optional private tour of its displays.

name: West India Dock Impounding Station
description: The recently automated impounding station controls the water level in the docks using the original Worthington Simpson pumps driven by Lancashire dynamo.
address: Western end of Marsh Wall, E14 8JT

name: Wimbledon Windmill
description: Rare example of a hollow post mill (1817). Grade II* listed, it now contains a museum depicting the history and development of windmills in Britain. Many working models, windmill machinery, equipment and tools.

name: Winchmore Hill Friends Meeting House & Burial Ground
description: Grade II listed, built 1790. A central double door under a bracketed cornice hood, large sash windows with delicate glazing bars. Panelled interior. Curved entrance wall allowed carriages to turn in the narrow lane. Notable burial ground.
address: Winchmore Hill Quaker Meeting House, 59 Church Hill, N21 1LE

name: Winscombe Street 1960s terrace
description: Terrace of five three-storey houses and a studio incorporating a sequence of communal and private spaces. Influential prototype for Camden social housing developments of the 1960s and 70s.

name: York House
description: Mid-17C house, a scheduled ancient monument, with fine staircase and 18C additions.

name: ‘OPEN’ Beyond Beck Road (part II)
description: Architecture and art produced in an unmodified street of 56 houses, railway arch studios, and private galleries between 1974 and 2023. Beck Rd is an iconic artist haven and its residents are key contributors to UK art history.
